Introduction to Python – Clear Notes
1. What is Python?

Python is a programming language.
It is:

Interpreted (code is executed line by line)
High-level (easy to read and write)
Object-oriented


Python also supports:

Procedural programming
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)


You can use Python in different ways depending on your purpose.


2. Why is Python So Popular?
Python is one of the fastest-growing programming languages because of:

Large number of developers
Huge collection of libraries
Many companies using it
Wide range of applications

Areas Where Python Is Used:

Machine Learning
Artificial Intelligence (AI)
Web Development
GUI (Graphical User Interface) Development
Data Science
Automation and Scripting

Because of this versatility, Python is called a General-Purpose Programming Language.

3. Python vs Other Languages

Languages like C, C++, Java, JavaScript already exist.
Python is not a new language:

Python was created in 1989
Java was created in 1995


Initially, Java dominated the enterprise market.
Python was mainly used for:

Learning programming
Simple scripting tasks




4. Rise of Python in AI & Machine Learning

With the growth of AI and Machine Learning, Python became popular again.
Research scientists prefer Python because:

They don’t want to spend much time learning complex syntax.
Python is simple and readable.


Python is easier than C, C++, and Java.

That is why:

Schools and colleges now teach Python as a first language.


5. Who Uses Python?
Python is used by many top companies, including:

Google
YouTube
Dropbox
Reddit


Example:


Google uses Python for several internal features.
Reddit is largely written in Python.


6. Why is Python Called “Python”?

The name Python does not come from the snake.
The creator of Python, Guido van Rossum, was a fan of:

Monty Python’s Flying Circus (a British comedy show).


He named the language Python based on this inspiration.


7. Is Python Easy to Learn?

Yes, Python is one of the easiest programming languages.
Suitable for:

Beginners
Non-technical backgrounds
Children


Even someone who has never written code before can start with Python.


8. Python Versions
Python has multiple versions:

Python 1.x
Python 2.x
Python 3.x

Python 2 vs Python 3:

Python 3 is not backward compatible with Python 2.
Because of this, Python 2 continued to be used for many years.
Python 2 had support until 2020.

Which Version Should You Learn?
✅ Python 3.x

It is the latest version.
Has more features.
Actively maintained and widely used.


